n of some Chinese convicts, deported from the Straits Settlement, and local Tamil Paraiyan|location=|title=Man in India, Volume 39|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=wpFWT-jhCeHc0QHg5e2CCg&id=UkwLAAAAIAAJ&dq=In+Gudalur%2C+enquiries+were+made+regarding+the+present+position+of+the+Tamil-Chinese+cross+described+by+Thurston+%281909%29.+It+may+be+recalled+here+that+Thurston+reported+the+above+cross+resulting+from+the+union+of+some+Chinese+convicts%2C+deported+from+the+Straits+Settlement%2C+and+local+Tamil+Paraiyan&q=enquiries+union+deported+local|isbn=|editor=Sarat Chandra Roy (Rai Bahadur)}}</ref>

According to Alabaster there were lard manufacturers and shoemakers in addition to carpenters. Running tanneries and working with [[leather]] was traditionally not considered a respectable profession among [[caste system|upper-caste]] [[Hindus]], and work was relegated to lower caste ''muchis'' and ''[[chamar]]s''. There was a high demand, however, for high quality leather goods in [[British Raj|colonial India]], one that the Chinese were able to fulfill. Alabaster also mentions licensed [[opium den]]s run by native Chinese and a ''Cheena Bazaar'' where contraband was readily available. Opium, however, was not illegal until after India's Independence from Great Britain in 1947. Immigration continued unabated through the turn of the century and during [[World War I]] partly due to political upheavals in China such as the [[First Opium War|First]] and [[Second Opium War]]s, [[First Sino-Japanese War]] and the [[Boxer Rebellion]]. Around the time of the First World War, the first Chinese-owned tanneries sprang up.<ref name="Banglapedia">{{cite book |last=Haraprasad |first=Ray |year=2012 |chapter=Chinese, The |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Chinese,_The |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>

In [[Assam]], local Assamese women married Chinese migrants during British colonial times. It later became hard to physically differentiate Chinese in Assam from locals during the time of their internment during the 1962 war, as the majority of these Chinese in Assam were mixed.<ref>{{cite news |last= CHOWDHURY |first= RITA |date=18 November 2012 |title=The Assamese Chinese story |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/the-assamese-chinese-story/article4106422.ece |newspaper= The Hindu |location= |publisher= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref>

===Guyana===
In Guyana, Chinese men married Indian women due to the lack of Chinese women in the early days of settlement.<ref>{{cite book|pages=272–273|year=1995|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press - MQUP|volume=Volume 22 of McGill-Queen's studies in ethnic history|issn=0846-8869|edition=illustrated|author=Brian L. Moore|quote=|location=|title=Cultural Power, Resistance, and Pluralism: Colonial Guyana, 1838-1900 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cx_9-X_-smoC&pg=PA272&dq=Chinese+men+also+cohabited+with+Indian+women,+and+in+a+few+instances+those+women+even&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A5ONVZHcOcO0-QGr97PoBg&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Chinese%20men%20also%20cohabited%20with%20Indian%20women%2C%20and%20in%20a%20few%20instances%20those%20women%20even&f=false|isbn=077351354X|editor=}}</ref> [[Creole peoples#Caribbean|Creole]] sexual relationships and marriages with Chinese and Indians were rare,<ref>{{cite book|page=181|pages=|year=1987|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Gordon & Breach Science Publishers|volume=Volume 4 of Caribbean studies|issn=0275-5793|edition=illustrated|author=Brian L. Moore|quote=|location=|title=Race, Power, and Social Segmentation in Colonial Society: Guyana After Slavery, 1838-1891|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=35u9AAAAIAAJ&q=As+Wood+and+Brereton+found+for+Trinidad,172+so+too+in+Guyana,+interracial+marriage+and+miscegenation+were+rare,173+particularly+between+Indians+and+Chinese+on+one+hand+and+Creoles+on+the+other.174+Nevertheless,+as+early+as+1841,+some+Indians+were+found+to+cohabit+with+Creole&dq=As+Wood+and+Brereton+found+for+Trinidad,172+so+too+in+Guyana,+interracial+marriage+and+miscegenation+were+rare,173+particularly+between+Indians+and+Chinese+on+one+hand+and+Creoles+on+the+other.174+Nevertheless,+as+early+as+1841,+some+Indians+were+found+to+cohabit+with+Creole&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AJqNVZPDM8vt-AH2qIHACg&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA|isbn=0677219806|editor=}}</ref> however it has become more common for Indian women and Chinese men to establish sexual relations with each other and some Chinese men took their Indian wives back with them to China.<ref>{{cite book|page=182|pages=|year=1987|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Gordon & Breach Science Publishers|volume=Volume 4 of Caribbean studies|issn=0275-5793|edition=illustrated|author=Brian L. Moore|quote=|location=|title=Race, Power, and Social Segmentation in Colonial Society: Guyana After Slavery, 1838-1891|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=35u9AAAAIAAJ&q=It+appears,+however,+that+cohabitation+between+Chinese+men+and+Indian+women+was+less+rare,+and+in+a+few+instances+the+women+even+accompanied+their+reputed+husbands+to+China.&dq=It+appears,+however,+that+cohabitation+between+Chinese+men+and+Indian+women+was+less+rare,+and+in+a+few+instances+the+women+even+accompanied+their+reputed+husbands+to+China.&hl=en&sa=X&ei=G5mNVZmkCcO1-AHJj4KQDA&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA|isbn=0677219806|editor=}}</ref>
Indian women and children were brought alongside Indian men as [[coolies]] while Chinese men made up 99% of Chinese coolies.<ref>{{cite book|page=8|edition=|pages=|year=2008|accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=Temple University Press|volume=|author=Lisa Yun|quote=|location=|title=The Coolie Speaks: Chinese Indentured Laborers and African Slaves in Cuba|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PWSC2ynmdgAC&pg=PA8&dq=indian+coolie+woman+chinese+men&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Nm2TVfLJEIeQyQTRwrHgAw&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=indian%20coolie%20woman%20chinese%20men&f=false|isbn=1592135838}}</ref>

The contrast with the female to male ratio among Indian and Chinese immigrants has been compared by historians.<ref>{{cite book|page=46|edition=illustrated|pages=|year=1993|accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|volume=|author=Walton Look Lai|editor=|quote=|location=|title=Indentured labor, Caribbean sugar: Chinese and Indian migrants to the British West Indies, 1838-1918|series=Johns Hopkins studies in Atlantic history and culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QJCxAAAAIAAJ&q=walton+look+lie+carribean+chinese+indian+women&dq=walton+look+lie+carribean+chinese+indian+women&hl=en&sa=X&ei=we2SVaqOPIj5yQS074HgAg&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBA|isbn=0801844657}}</ref>

===Mauritius===
In the late 19th to early 20th century, [[Sino-Mauritian|Chinese men in Mauritius]] married [[Indo-Mauritian|Indian]] women due to both a lack of Chinese women and higher numbers of Indian women on the island.<ref>{{cite book|page=199|edition=|pages=|year=2009|accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=Volume 1 of European expansion and indigenous response, v. 1|author=Marina Carter, James Ng Foong Kwong|quote=|location=|title= Abacus and Mah Jong: Sino-Mauritian Settlement and Economic Consolidation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SN53oTMjAyMC&pg=PA199#v=onepage&q&f=false|archiveurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=RtOwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA199&lpg=PA199&dq=chinese+shopkeepers+indian+creole+women+mauritius&source=bl&ots=ux4RYxvT3x&sig=ozjqdTOIbdbIVubSnNR1_YEXIz4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3EeUVZu2FcfEsAXp2paYDQ&ved=0CEwQ6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=chinese%20shopkeepers%20indian%20creole%20women%20mauritius&f=false|archivedate=2009|isbn=9004175725}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=33|edition=|pages=|year=2009 |accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|volume=|author=Paul Younger Professor Emeritus of Religious Studies McMaster University|quote=|location=|title=New Homelands : Hindu Communities in Mauritius, Guyana, Trinidad, South Africa, Fiji, and East Africa: Hindu Communities in Mauritius, Guyana, Trinidad, South Africa, Fiji, and East Africa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F0X9eLq57ocC&pg=PA33&lpg=PA33&dq=chinese+shopkeepers+indian+creole+women+mauritius&source=bl&ots=1XIYQHpfZk&sig=djuZK2UeYEDYnl_aw682z1BDjKo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9EeUVfLsOsu4sAWowIBg&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=chinese%20shopkeepers%20indian%20creole%20women%20mauritius&f=false|archiveurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=3VTiBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT40&dq=chinese+men+cohabit+indian+women+mauritius&hl=en&sa=X&ei=XFWTVfS7OYW4yQTe14HQDw&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=chinese%20men%20cohabit%20indian%20women%20mauritius&f=false|archivedate=2009|isbn=0199741921}}</ref> At first the prospect of relations with Indian women was unappealing to the original all male Chinese migrants yet they eventually had to establish sexual unions with Indian women since there were no Chinese women coming.<ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date= |title= What Inter-Ethnic Marriage In Mauritius Tells Us About The Nature of Ethnicity|url= http://arinave.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/INCORE-Paper-2001-PDF1.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518083011/http://arinave.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/INCORE-Paper-2001-PDF1.pdf|dead-url=yes|archivedate=18 May 2014 |journal= |publisher= |volume= |issue= |page= 15 |doi= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> The 1921 census in Mauritius counted that Indian women there had a total of 148 children sired by Chinese men.<ref>{{cite book|page=174|edition=|pages=|year=2008|accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=Éditions de l'océan Indien|volume=|author=Huguette Ly-Tio-Fane Pineo, Edouard Lim Fat|quote=|location=|title= From alien to citizen: the integration of the Chinese in Mauritius |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FNswAQAAIAAJ&q=children+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+men+with+women+of+the+general+population+and+148+others+were+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+men+with+Indian+women.+(62)+The+first+signs+of+a+new+culture+born+from+the+symbiosis+of+Eastern+and+...&dq=children+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+men+with+women+of+the+general+population+and+148+others+were+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+men+with+Indian+women.+(62)+The+first+signs+of+a+new+culture+born+from+the+symbiosis+of+Eastern+and+...&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HsRyU7OnAfSisQTH-IEI&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA|isbn=9990305692}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=287|edition=|pages=|year=1985|accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=Ed. de l'océan indien|volume=|author=Huguette Ly Tio Fane-Pineo|quote=|location=|title= Chinese Diaspora in Western Indian Ocean |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3U4MAQAAIAAJ&q=He+thus+recorded+that+in+1921+there+were+386+children+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+with+women+of+the+general+population+and+148+others+were+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+with+Indian+women+(62).+The+first+signs+of+a+new+culture+born+...&dq=He+thus+recorded+that+in+1921+there+were+386+children+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+with+women+of+the+general+population+and+148+others+were+born+from+the+union+of+Chinese+with+Indian+women+(62).+The+first+signs+of+a+new+culture+born+...&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AcRyU4OfIqWysASfoYCABw&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAA|isbn=9990305692}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last= |first= |last2= |first2= |date= |title= What Inter-Ethnic Marriage In Mauritius Tells Us About The Nature of Ethnicity|url= http://arinave.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/INCORE-Paper-2001-PDF1.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518083011/http://arinave.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/INCORE-Paper-2001-PDF1.pdf|dead-url=yes|archivedate=18 May 2014 |journal= |publisher= |volume= |issue= |page= 16 |doi= |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> These Chinese were mostly traders.<ref>{{cite book|page=41|edition=|pages=|year=2002|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Nelson Mandela Centre for African Culture, Ministry of Arts & Culture|volume=|author=Monique Dinan|quote=|location=|title= Mauritius in the Making: Across the Censuses, 1846-2000 |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=L5KNVdu2HcXs-AHziIEw&id=gnawAAAAIAAJ&dq=The+Chinese+trader+has+also+intermarried+or+cohabited+with+the+African%2C+Indian+or+mixed-races%2C+but+as+they+have+always+formed+a+very+small+minority+of+the+total+population%2C+the+effect+is+not+marked.+10%29+It+is+extremely+difficult+in+a+Census&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=intermarried+cohabited|isbn=9990390460}}</ref> Colonialist stereotypes in the sugar colonies of Indians emerged such as "the degraded coolie woman" and the "coolie wife beater", due to Indian women being murdered by their husbands after they ran away to other richer men since the ratio of Indian women to men was low.<ref>{{cite book|page=203|edition=|pages=|year=2009|accessdate=17 May 2014|publisher=BRILL|volume=Volume 1 of European expansion and indigenous response, v. 1|author=Marina Carter, James Ng Foong Kwong|quote=|location= |title=Abacus and Mah Jong: Sino-Mauritian Settlement and Economic Consolidation |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SN53oTMjAyMC&pg=PA203&dq=indian+coolie+woman+chinese+men&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Nm2TVfLJEIeQyQTRwrHgAw&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=indian%20coolie%20woman%20chinese%20men&f=false|isbn=9004175725}}</ref> It was much more common for Chinese and Indians to intermarry than within their own group. Intermarriage between people of between different Chinese and Indian language groups is rare; it is so rare that the cases of intermarriage between Cantonese and Hakka can be individually named. Similarly, intermarriage between Hakka Chinese and Indians hardly occurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=H_xtAAAAMAAJ&q=Similarly,+intermarriage+between+Hakka+Chinese+and+Indians+hardly&dq=Similarly,+intermarriage+between+Hakka+Chinese+and+Indians+hardly&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZx9ii38TSAhWHAsAKHRK2D7QQ6AEIGjAA|title=Blood, sweat, and mahjong: family and enterprise in an overseas Chinese community|first=Ellen|last=Oxfeld|date=29 May 1993|publisher=Cornell University Press|accessdate=29 May 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>

===Trinidad===
In [[Trinidad]], some [[Chinese Trinidadian and Tobagonian|Chinese men]] had relationships with [[Indo-Trinidadian and Tobagonian|Indian coolie women]] of [[Madras|Madrasee origin]], siring children with them, and it was reported that "A few children are to be met with born of Madras and Creole parents and some also of Madras and Chinese parents - the Madrasee being the mother", by the missionary John Morton in 1876, Morton noted that it seemed strange since there were more Indian coolie men than Indian coolie women that Indian coolie women would marry Chinese men, but claimed it was most likely because the Chinese could provide amenities to the women since the Chinese owned shops and they were enticed by these.<ref>{{cite book|page=14|pages=|year=2014|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|volume=|issn=|edition=|author=|editors=Julitta Rydlewska, Barbara Braid|others=|quote=|location=|title=Unity in Diversity, Volume 1: Cultural Paradigm and Personal Identity, Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WBVQBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA14&dq=some+also+of+madras+and+chinese+parents+the+madrasee+being+the+mother&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Y1KTVYG2MYr2yQT0ypKQBw&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=some%20also%20of%20madras%20and%20chinese%20parents%20the%20madrasee%20being%20the%20mother&f=false|archiveurl=http://www.cambridgescholars.com/download/sample/61376|archivedate=2014|isbn=1443867292}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=238|pages=|year=1995|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Nycan|volume=|issn=|edition=|author=Dennison Moore|editors=|others=|quote=|location=|title=Origins and Development of Racial Ideology in Trinidad |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=pRKTVZGPJoG--AGOr6Zo&id=kTV7AAAAMAAJ&dq=some+also+of+madras+and+chinese+parents+the+madrasee+being+the+mother&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=being+mother|isbn=0968006000}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|page=263|pages=|year=1999|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Sir Arthur Lewis Institute of Social and Economic Studies, The University of the West Indies|volume=|issn=|edition=|author=Selwyn D. Ryan|editors=|others=|quote=|location=|title=The Jhandi and the Cross: The Clash of Cultures in Post-creole Trinidad and Tobago|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=pRKTVZGPJoG--AGOr6Zo&id=lDVsAAAAMAAJ&dq=some+also+of+madras+and+chinese+parents+the+madrasee+being+the+mother&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=being+mother+coolie|isbn=9766180318}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|pages=65–66|year=2014|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=NYU Press|volume=|issn=|edition=|author=|editors=Rebecca Chiyoko King-O'Riain, Stephen Small, Minelle Mahtani|others=|quote=|location=|title=Global Mixed Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0bbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q&f=false|archiveurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=SszaAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT80&dq=some+also+of+madras+and+chinese+parents+the+madrasee+being+the+mother&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pRKTVZGPJoG--AGOr6Zo&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=some%20also%20of%20madras%20and%20chinese%20parents%20the%20madrasee%20being%20the%20mother&f=false|archivedate=2014|isbn=0814770479}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Regis |first=Ferne Louanne |last2= |first2= |date=April 2011 |title=The Dougla in Trinidad's Consciousness |url=http://uwispace.sta.uwi.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2139/11131/Article%201%20-%20regis.pdf?sequence=1 |archiveurl=http://www.mainlib.uwi.tt/epubs/historyaction/papers/printversion2.pdf|archivedate=8 March 2011|journal=History in Action |publisher=The University of the West Indies (St. Augustine, Trinidad and Tobago) Dept. of History |volume= 2 |issue= 1 |issn=2221-7886|pages= |doi= |accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Indian women were married by indentured Chinese men in Trinidad.<ref>{{cite book|page=315|pages=|year=2013|publisher=Coach House Books|volume=|issn=|edition=illustrated|author=Mike Hoolboom|editor=Mike Hoolboom|quote=|location=|title=Practical Dreamers: Conversations with Movie Artists|series=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n8eOKiK3llYC&pg=PA315&dq=chinese+men+married+indian+women+trinidad&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FmWTVab4HpOiyQTGoI-gBQ&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=chinese%20men%20married%20indian%20women%20trinidad&f=false|isbn=1770561811 |accessdate=6 March 2017}}</ref> Few Chinese women migrated to Trinidad while the majority of Chinese migrants were men.<ref>{{cite book|page=54|pages=|year=2014|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=NYU Press|volume=|issn=|edition=|author=|editors=Rebecca Chiyoko King-O'Riain, Stephen Small, Minelle Mahtani|others=|quote=|location=|title=Global Mixed Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0bbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA54&dq=chinese+men+married+indian+women+trinidad&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FmWTVab4HpOiyQTGoI-gBQ&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=chinese%20men%20married%20indian%20women%20trinidad&f=false|isbn=0814770479}}</ref> The migration of Chinese to Trinidad resulted in intermarriage between them and others.<ref>{{cite book|page=26|pages=|year=1992|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Inprint Caribbean|volume=|issn=|edition=2|author=Adrian Curtis Bird|editors=|others=|quote=|location=|title=Trinidad sweet: the people, their culture, their island|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uVMYAAAAYAAJ&q=They+intermarried+more+readily+into+other+ethnic+groups+and+produced+many+of+the+most+exotically+glamorous+results.+...+British+Guiana+moved+more+quickly+and+brought+over+20,000+Portuguese+into+their+territory.&dq=They+intermarried+more+readily+into+other+ethnic+groups+and+produced+many+of+the+most+exotically+glamorous+results.+...+British+Guiana+moved+more+quickly+and+brought+over+20,000+Portuguese+into+their+territory.&hl=en&sa=X&ei=r8iSVe2eGtiiyATRqpZI&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA|isbn=0814770479}}</ref> Chinese in Trinidad became relatively open to having marital relations with other races and Indian women began having families with Chinese in the 1890s.<ref>{{cite book|page=95|pages=|year=2000|accessdate=1 June 2015|publisher=Kaisa Para Sa Kaunlaran, Incorporated|volume=|issn=|edition=2|author=|editor=Teresita Ang See|others=International Society for the Studies of Chinese Overseas, Kaisa Para Sa Kaunlaran|quote=|location=|title=Intercultural Relations, Cultural Transformation, and Identity: The Ethnic Chinese : Selected Papers Presented at the 1998 ISSCO Conference|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-VhwAAAAMAAJ&q=In+comparison+with+the+South+Asian+Indians,+the+Chinese+attitudes+toward+interracial+marriages+or+unions+were+far+less+racially+exclusive+and+devoid+of+many+of+the+caste+taboos+of+the+Indians.+By+the+1+890s,+there+was+already+a+sizeable+mixed+Chinese+community.+As+in+Southeast+Asia,+many+Chinese+started+second+families+overseas+with+local+women,+some+of+whom+were+South+Asian+Indians,+as+well+as+with+Creole+women.&dq=In+comparison+with+the+South+Asian+Indians,+the+Chinese+attitudes+toward+interracial+marriages+or+unions+were+far+less+racially+exclusive+and+devoid+of+many+of+the+caste+taboos+of+the+Indians.+By+the+1+890s,+there+was+already+a+sizeable+mixed+Chinese+community.+As+in+Southeast+Asia,+many+Chinese+started+second+families+overseas+with+local+women,+some+of+whom+were+South+Asian+Indians,+as+well+as+with+Creole+women.&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2DaUVcDrCMacsAWA1YPwDA&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA|isbn=9718857214}}</ref>

