'''Jacob of London''' was the first known ''[[Presbyter Judaeorum]]'' of the [[Jews of England]]; appointed to that position by [[King John of England|King John]] in 1199, who also gave him a [[safe-conduct]]. He appears to have died in 1217, when [[Josce of London]] is mentioned as his successor. He is possibly identical with the rabbi Jacob of London who translated the whole [[Haggadah]] into the vernacular so that women and children could understand it ([[Isserles]], "Darke Mosheh," to Tur Orah hayyim, 473).
==Resources== *[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=72&letter=J&search=Jacob%20of%20London Jacobs, Joseph. "Jacob of London."] ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]].'' Funk and Wagnalls, 1901–1906, which gives the following bibliography: :*Prynne, Short Demurrer, ii. 3-5; :*H. Adler, in Papers of the Anglo-Jewish Historical Exhibition, pp. 262-263.
