'''María de Echarri y Martínez''' (9 September 1878 – 1955) was a Spanish catholic propagandist and columnist, advocate of feminist causes.{{Sfn|Franco Rubio|2004|pp=473-474}}

== Biography ==
Born 9 September 1878 in [[San Lorenzo de El Escorial]], she was teacher by profession.{{Sfn|A. de M.|1925|p=9}} She was a publicist associated to the "Acción Católica de la Mujer",{{Sfn|Blasco Herranz|2005|p=122}}{{Sfn|Rosique Navarro|Peralta Ruiz|2012|p=355}} in addition to being an advocate of the working woman from a Catholic perspective.{{Sfn|Núñez|1998|p=405}} She became one of the first female city councillors of Madrid in 1924.{{Sfn|Rosique Navarro|Peralta Ruiz|2012|p=356}} In 1927 she became one of the 13 women represented in the so-called [[Consultative National Assembly]] of the [[Miguel Primo de Rivera|Primo de Rivera]] dictatorship,{{Sfnm|Monterde García|2010|1p=266|Díaz Fernández|2005|2p=187}} in office from 10 October 1927 to 15 February 1930.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/SDocum/ArchCon/SDHistoDipu/SDBuscHisDip?_piref73_1340033_73_1340032_1340032.next_page=/wc/servidorCGI&CMD=VERLST&BASE=DIPH&FMT=DIPHXDSP.fmt&DOCS=1-1&DOCORDER=FIFO&OPDEF=Y&QUERY=%28MAR%C3%ADA+ECHARRI%29.DIPU.|publisher=[[Congreso de los Diputados]]|title=Echarri Martínez, María de}}</ref> She died in [[San Sebastián]] in 1955.<ref name=abc>{{Cite web|url = http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1955/09/02/018.html|work = [[ABC (Spain)|ABC]]|title = Necrológica. Doña María de Echarri|date = 2 September 1955}}</ref>

She was a recipient of the ''[[Pro Ecclesia et Pontifice]]'' medal.<ref name=abc />

